<TEI xmlns="http://www.tei-c.org/ns/1.0" xmlns:frus="http://history.state.gov/frus/ns/1.0"><text><body><div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1928-10-19T08:30:00-05:00" frus:doc-dateTime-min="1928-10-19T08:30:00-05:00" n="397" subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d397">
                        <note rend="inline" type="source">710.1012 Washington/118: Telegram</note>
                        <head><hi rend="italic">The Minister in Uruguay</hi> (<persName type="from"><hi rend="italic">Grant-Smith</hi></persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the <gloss type="to">Secretary of
                                State</gloss></hi></head>
                        <opener><dateline rendition="#right"><placeName><hi rend="smallcaps">Montevideo</hi></placeName>, <date calendar="gregorian" when="1928-10-19T10:00:00-03:30"><hi rend="italic">October 19,
                                        1928—10 a.m.</hi></date><lb/>[Received 10:40
                                a.m.]</dateline></opener>
                        <p>32. Your instruction No. 129, April 14 last.<note n="19" xml:id="d397fn19">See footnote 66, <ref target="#pg_621">p.
                                    621</ref>.</note> The Under Secretary for Foreign Affairs
                            informed me yesterday that the attitude of the <pb facs="0772" n="644" xml:id="pg_644"/> Uruguayan Government relative to the arbitration
                            of juridical questions would be the same as at the Rio de Janeiro
                            Conference. The delegate[s] would be named shortly and would go from
                            here.</p>
                        <closer><signed><hi rend="smallcaps">Grant-Smith</hi></signed></closer>
                    </div>
                </body></text></TEI>